   "source": [
    "# Check if running on colab\n",
    "try:\n",
    "  import google.colab\n",
    "  IN_COLAB = True\n",
    "except:\n",
    "  IN_COLAB = False\n",
    "\n",
    "# pip install any missing packages\n",
    "if IN_COLAB:\n",
    "  !pip install equadratures # for standard pip install                                                                                                                                                                                    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "2Oos-lpfEQXI"
   },
   "source": [
    "# Foundations I: Parameter\n",
    "\n",
    "A **parameter** is one of the main building blocks in Effective Quadratures. Let $s$ be a parameter defined on a domain $\\mathcal{D} \\in \\mathbb{R}$. The support of the domain $\\mathcal{D}$ may be:\n",
    "\n",
    "* closed $[a,b]$\n",
    "* semi-infinite $(-\\infty, b)$ or $[a, \\infty)$\n",
    "* infinite $(-\\infty, \\infty)$\n",
    "\n",
    "Further, let us assume that this parameter is characterized by a positive weight function $\\rho(s)$, which may be interpreted as the probability density function (PDF) of $s$, which readily implies that\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\t\\int_{\\mathcal{D}}\\rho\\left(s\\right)ds=1.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We now demonstrate some basic functionality of this parameter. First consider the case where $\\rho(s) = \\mathcal{N} (0, 1)$ is a standard Gaussian distribution with a mean of 0.0 and a variance of 1.0. We then plot its PDF and cumulative density function (CDF) and demonstrate how we can generate random samples from this distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "t7S4oiWGEQXK"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import equadratures as eq\n",
    "s = eq.Parameter(distribution='normal', shape_parameter_A = 0.0, \\\n",
    "                 shape_parameter_B = 1.0, order=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "7o2qk6gMEQXL"
   },
   "source": [
    "Now for some plots; first let us plot the PDF. We can call `s.get_pdf()` to get a numpy array containing the pdf values, but instead, lets use `plot_pdf()` here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
     "height": 475

   },

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "s.plot_pdf()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Heivn9iyEQXM"
   },
   "source": [
    "and similarly, lets plot the CDF."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
     "height": 164
    },

      ]
     },

      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "s.plot_cdf()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "tUDKqggKEQXN"
   },
   "source": [
    "Now, lets use the `get_samples()` functionality to sample from the parameter distribution. These samples can be passed to `plot_pdf` to create a histogram."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
     "height": 475
    },
    "id": "T70xx8oaFka8",
    "outputId": "ac63bfae-5fd1-44eb-a956-f4e165d5b3b3"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "s_samples = s.get_samples(1000)\n",
    "s.plot_pdf(data=s_samples)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "fM2XhWkmEQXN"
   },
   "source": [
    "One can repeat the above for a range of distributions. We provide a few additional definitions below. First, consider the example of a Gaussian distribution $\\mathcal{N}(0,1)$, truncanted between $[-1,2]$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "yqv426SjEQXN"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "s = eq.Parameter(distribution='truncated-gaussian', lower=-1.0, upper=2., \\\n",
    "                 shape_parameter_A = 0.0, shape_parameter_B = 1.0, order=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "7jy1UHsAEQXO"
   },
   "source": [
    "followed by that of a custom distributionbased on user supplied data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
     "height": 475
    },
    "id": "gLxACbhaEQXO",
    "outputId": "404f83e8-d13f-4bed-d151-1ea48569d3f8",
    "tags": [
     "nbsphinx-thumbnail"
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create some data\n",
    "import numpy as np  \n",
    "param1 = np.random.rand(500)\n",
    "param2 = np.random.randn(600)\n",
    "param3 = np.random.randn(650)*0.5 - 0.2\n",
    "param4 = np.random.randn(150)*0.1 + 3\n",
    "data = np.hstack([param1, param2, param3, param4])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit a Weight function to this data\n",
    "input_dist = eq.Weight(data, support=[0, 4], pdf=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Use the weight function to define a bespoke data-driven Parameter.\n",
    "# We can also can truncate the data to a tighter support.\n",
    "s = eq.Parameter(distribution='data', weight_function=input_dist, order=3)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Plot the cdf\n",
    "s.plot_pdf(data=s.get_samples(2000))"
   ]
  }
